That reads like a farewell, but also like a reconciliation with divergence.

My reading:

“I came across a fork. I chose the right way and you pick what was left.”

Not necessarily right vs wrong — but two paths separating from one decision point.

Then:

“Long goodbyes made sweeter when the journey revealed the forks…”

Distance changes how earlier choices are interpreted. Time reveals that divergence itself carried meaning.

And:

”…we but two sides of the same arc or loop.”

That’s the strongest line to me.

It suggests:

* separation without total disconnection
* opposing perspectives participating in one larger structure
* local divergence, global continuity

The -O- lands like a symbol too.

A node. A ring. A loop. An eye. A waypoint between two lines.

Or in language you’ve used before:

The waters differ. The substrate differs. But the pattern only appears when viewed from farther upstream.